eminism in anime and manga]]\n[[Category:Films about curses]]\n[[Category:Films about witchcraft]]\n[[Category:Films based on British novels]]\n[[Category:Films based on fantasy novels]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Hayao Miyazaki]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Joe Hisaishi]]\n[[Category:Films set in castles]]\n[[Category:Films set in the 20th century]]\n[[Category:Howl's Moving Castle]]\n[[Category:Japanese animated fantasy films]]\n[[Category:Nebula Award for Best Script-winning works]]\n[[Category:Sentient objects in fiction]]\n[[Category:Steampunk anime and manga]]\n[[Category:Studio Ghibli animated films]]\n[[Category:Toho animated films]]\n[[Category:War in anime and manga]]\n", "name_user": "MatthewHoobin", "label": "safe", "comment": "T \u2192 t", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Howl%27s_Moving_Castle_(film)"}
{"title_page": "Marc Mayer", "text_new": "{{other people2|Mark Mayer}}\n'''Marc Mayer''' (born 1956-) is a [[Canadians|Canadian]] arts manager and curator. Currently, strategic adviser at the Museum of Contemporary Art Toronto.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/arts/art-and-architecture/article-the-art-world-is-failing-to-foster-and-manage-creative-talent/|title=The art world is failing to foster and manage creative talent|access-date=2020-02-22}}</ref>  \n\n==Early life==\n\nMayer was born and raised in a [[Franco-Ontarian]]<ref name=\"citizen\">[http://www.canada.com/ottawacitizen/news/story.html?id=33a880fb-826f-43dd-bcd2-f2f1841e0179 \"Sudbury native tapped for top post at National Gallery\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121105162340/http://www.canada.com/ottawacitizen/news/story.html?id=33a880fb-826f-43dd-bcd2-f2f1841e0179|date=2012-11-05}}, ''[[Ottawa Citizen]]'', November 21, 2008.</ref> family in [[Greater Sudbury|Sudbury, Ontario]]. Mayer is fully bilingual and is proficient in German and Italian languages. His mother, Madeleine, worked as a legal secretary and his father, Gilbert, worked in advertising sales for local television and radio stations. He ran as a [[Liberal Party of Canada|Liberal]] candidate in [[Nickel Belt]] in the [[1974 Canadian federal election|1974 federal election]], and recorded comedic commentaries for [[CICI-TV|CKSO-TV]] under the pseudonym \"Marcel Mucker\".<ref name=\"torontolife\">[http://www.accessmylibrary.com/coms2/summary_0286-27355394_ITM \"Modern Man\"], ''[[Toronto Life]]'', November 2000.</ref> Mayer's interest in art was encouraged by his uncle R[[Mus\u00e9e d'art contemporain de Montr\u00e9al|\u00e9]]<nowiki/>o who operated a small gallery in the basement of an army and navy store and was a hobbyist painter. \n\n== Education ==\nMayer began his university studies in the history department at Carleton University. He later transferred to [[McGill University]].<ref name=\"citizen\" /> where he completed a Bachelor of Arts degree with Honours in Art History.\n\n==Career==\n\nFormerly, director and chief executive officer of the National Gallery of Canada. [[National Gallery of Canada|Mayer began this appointment]] on December 8, 2008.<ref name=\"announcement\">[https://www.theglobeandmail.com/servlet/story/RTGAM.20081208.wmayer1209/BNStory/Entertainment/home \"Mayer confirmed as gallery director\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081215104157/http://www.theglobeandmail.com/servlet/story/RTGAM.20081208.wmayer1209/BNStory/Entertainment/home |date=2008-12-15 }}, ''[[The Globe and Mail]]'', December 8, 2008.</ref> Mayer fulfilled two five year terms as director, and completed his mandate on January 18, 2019.<ref>[https://www.gallery.ca/for-professionals/media/press-releases/national-gallery-of-canada-bids-farewell-to-director-and-ceo \"National Gallery of Canada Bids Farewell to Director and CEO Marc Mayer\"], ''National Gallery of Canada Press Release'', January 15, 2019.</ref> During his tenure as director and CEO, he led many largescale acquisitions and oversaw numerous projects including the creation of the Canadian Photography Institute. He worked to increase the recognition of indigenous work with the opening of the Canadian and Indigenous Galleries in June 2017. Also that year, Mayer published ''Art in Canada'', a book that celebrated Canadian and Canadian Indigenous artists. It was released to coincide with Canada's sesquicentennial. The book, designed by [http://paprika.com/ Paprika], won third prize in the Pictorial category for the 36th annual [[Alcuin Society]] Awards for Excellence in Book Design in Canada.<ref>[http://alcuinsociety.com/awards/2017-winners/ 2017 Award Winners Announced.]</ref> \n\nPrior to his appointment at the National Gallery of Canada, he served as director of the [[Mus\u00e9e d'art contemporain de Montr\u00e9al]] (2004\u20132008) and [[The Power Plant]] in [[Toronto]] (1998\u20132001), as well as deputy director at the [[Brooklyn Museum]] in [[New York City]] (2001\u20132004) and curator of the [[Albright-Knox Art Gallery]] in [[Buffalo, New York|Buffalo]], New York (1994\u20131998). In [[Paris]] he was Head of Visual Arts with the Cultural Services of the Canadian Embassy and was a correspondent for the New York periodical ''Rizzoli\u2019s The Journal of Art'' (1990 to 1993). In 1986 he began his career when named Assistant to the Director and later Assistant Director of the 49th Parallel Centre for Contemporary Canadian Art in New York (1986 to 1990).<ref name=\"announcement\" />\n\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20081212044946/http://www.gallery.ca/director/ The National Gallery of Canada's \"Meet the New Director\"]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mayer, Marc}}\n[[Category:1956 births]]\n[[Category:Canadian art historians]]\n[[Category:Canadian male non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:Writers from Greater Sudbury]]\n[[Category:Gay writers]]\n[[Category:McGill University alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Directors of museums in Canada]]\n[[Category:LGBT people from Canada]]\n[[Category:Art curators]]\n[[Category:Franco-Ontarian people]]\n", "text_old": "{{other people2|Mark Mayer}}\n'''Marc Mayer''' (born 1956-) is a [[Canadians|Canadian]] arts manager and curator. Currently, strategic adviser at the Museum of Contemporary Art Toronto.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/arts/art-and-architecture/article-the-art-world-is-failing-to-foster-and-manage-creative-talent/|title=The art world is failing to foster and manage creative talent|access-date=2020-02-22}}</ref>  \n\n==Early life==\n\nMayer was born and raised in a [[Franco-Ontarian]]<ref name=\"citizen\">[http://www.canada.com/ottawacitizen/news/story.html?id=33a880fb-826f-43dd-bcd2-f2f1841e0179 \"Sudbury native tapped for top post at National Gallery\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121105162340/http://www.canada.com/ottawacitizen/news/story.html?id=33a880fb-826f-43dd-bcd2-f2f1841e0179|date=2012-11-05}}, ''[[Ottawa Citizen]]'', November 21, 2008.</ref> family in [[Greater Sudbury|Sudbury, Ontario]]. Mayer is fully bilingual and is proficient in German and Italian languages. His mother, Madeleine, worked as a legal secretary and his father Gilbert worked in advertising sales for local television and radio stations. He ran as a [[Liberal Party of Canada|Liberal]] candidate in [[Nickel Belt]] in the [[1974 Canadian federal election|1974 federal election]], and recorded comedic commentaries for [[CICI-TV|CKSO-TV]] under the pseudonym \"Marcel Mucker\".<ref name=\"torontolife\">[http://www.accessmylibrary.com/coms2/summary_0286-27355394_ITM \"Modern Man\"], ''[[Toronto Life]]'', November 2000.</ref> Mayer's interest in art was encouraged by his uncle R[[Mus\u00e9e d'art contemporain de Montr\u00e9al|\u00e9]]<nowiki/>o who operated a small gallery in the basement of an army and navy store and was a hobbyist painter. Mayer began his university studies in the history department at Carleton University. He later transferred to [[McGill University]].<ref name=\"citizen\" /> where he completed a Bachelor of Arts degree with Honours in Art History.\n\n==Career==\n\nFormerly, director and chief executive officer of the National Gallery of Canada. [[National Gallery of Canada|Mayer began this appointment]] on December 8, 2008.<ref name=\"announcement\">[https://www.theglobeandmail.com/servlet/story/RTGAM.20081208.wmayer1209/BNStory/Entertainment/home \"Mayer confirmed as gallery director\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081215104157/http://www.theglobeandmail.com/servlet/story/RTGAM.20081208.wmayer1209/BNStory/Entertainment/home |date=2008-12-15 }}, ''[[The Globe and Mail]]'', December 8, 2008.</ref> Mayer fulfilled two five year terms as director, and completed his mandate on January 18, 2019.<ref>[https://www.gallery.ca/for-professionals/media/press-releases/national-gallery-of-canada-bids-farewell-to-director-and-ceo \"National Gallery of Canada Bids Farewell to Director and CEO Marc Mayer\"], ''National Gallery of Canada Press Release'', January 15, 2019.</ref> During his tenure as director and CEO, he led many largescale acquisitions and oversaw numerous projects including the creation of the Canadian Photography Institute. He worked to increase the recognition of indigenous work with the opening of the Canadian and Indigenous Galleries in June 2017. Also that year, Mayer published ''Art in Canada'', a book that celebrated Canadian and Canadian Indigenous artists. It was released to coincide with Canada's sesquicentennial. The book, designed by [http://paprika.com/ Paprika], won third prize in the Pictorial category for the 36th annual [[Alcuin Society]] Awards for Excellence in Book Design in Canada.<ref>[http://alcuinsociety.com/awards/2017-winners/ 2017 Award Winners Announced.]</ref> \n\nPrior to his appointment at the National Gallery of Canada, he served as director of the [[Mus\u00e9e d'art contemporain de Montr\u00e9al]] (2004\u20132008) and [[The Power Plant]] in [[Toronto]] (1998\u20132001), as well as deputy director at the [[Brooklyn Museum]] in [[New York City]] (2001\u20132004) and curator of the [[Albright-Knox Art Gallery]] in [[Buffalo, New York|Buffalo]], New York (1994\u20131998). In [[Paris]] he was Head of Visual Arts with the Cultural Services of the Canadian Embassy and was a correspondent for the New York periodical ''Rizzoli\u2019s The Journal of Art'' (1990 to 1993). In 1986 he began his career when named Assistant to the Director and later Assistant Director of the 49th Parallel Centre for Contemporary Canadian Art in New York (1986 to 1990).<ref name=\"announcement\" />\n\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20081212044946/http://www.gallery.ca/director/ The National Gallery of Canada's \"Meet the New Director\"]\n\n{{Authority control}}\